	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 12-01-2004 <font color="#FEDE01">02:59 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">Leapy said in post <a href="http://www.eqcleric.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&postid=#post" target="_blank">#1 </a>:<b>How in the heck do you get rid of a leader who hasn't logged in for more than half a year?  The GMs won't do it for us, and we don't want to all disband and lose our guild name.  Anyone have any suggestions?</b></td></tr></table> <br />
To be honest, I can understand why the GMs won't kick him for you.  Despite the fact that your old GL hasn't logged on in months, and even though it's pretty inconsiderate of him to do so, the guild name does belong to him.  If he didn't transfer the guild to somebody else before he left, then the GMs can't do it for him.  He could have disbanded the guild, taking the name with him.  The GMs don't allow recycling of old guild names, so you still wouldn't have been able to reform under that same name, if he had.  <br />
<br />
You could look at it from the perspective of the old GL doing you a favor, leaving the guild tag up, so that at least the GMs allowed you to continue with the tag, with a "co-GL" running things.<br />
<br />
But, those are basically your only two options:  everybody deguild and reform under a new guild tag, or continue as you are, status quo, with the old GL still on the rolls.  Keep in mind, though, that on the off-chance your old GL ever <b><i>does</i></b> return, he will immediately be the man in charge, even after his months-long absence, with the power to disband your guild on a whim.  <br />
<br />
Personally, I wouldn't take that chance.  I'd disband and reform under a new tag while I could do it in an organized fashion, rather than giving him the chance to disband my guild, and forcing me to do it.  The last couple of new guild startups I was a part of (most recently a couple of months ago ) took roughly three weeks from the initial petitions to getting the new GL tagged by a GM.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><img src="/forums/images/sig_separator.gif" width="282" height="11" Alt="Hey! Watch where you point that thing!"><br>
<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">

<font color="orange"><b>Evanya Fleurdemorte</b> (wanna check out my <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1016330" target="_blank">stuff</a>?)<br />
Level 55 Dark Elf Cleric of Innoruuk<br />
Rage of Karana, Karana Server</font><br />
<br />
<font color="yellow"><font size="1"><i>Before you judge someone, walk a mile in their shoes.  That way, when you judge them, you're a mile away and you have their shoes.</i></font></font>
</font></p></p>
